rchwiail,Maelor Gymraeg,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales"},"nl":{"about 1260–":"circa 1260–Overleden","1260–Male":"1260–Overleden","1287–Male":"1287–Overleden","1310–Female":"1310–Overleden","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1333–Female":"1333–Overleden","1335–Female":"1335–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1330–Female":"1330–Overleden","about 1260":"circa 1260","1335":"1335","ABT    1330":"circa 1330","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1287":"1287","1330":"1330","1260":"1260","{Blddn ap Cnfn}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italië","of Marchwiail,Maelor Gymraeg,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1260–":"about 1260–Deceased","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1287–Male":"1287–Deceased","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1333–Female":"1333–Deceased","1335–Female":"1335–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","about 1260":"about 1260","1335":"1335","ABT    1330":"about 1330","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1287":"1287","1330":"1330","1260":"1260","{Blddn ap Cnfn}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italy","of Marchwiail,Maelor Gymraeg,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Madog","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French Canadian: variant of   Madore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Llywelyn ap Madog was born about 1260 as the son of Madog ap Adda and Gwen ferch Llywelyn. He had at least 2 daughters with Lleucu ferch Madog."},"et":{"about 1260–":"umbes 1260–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1333–Female":"1333–Surnud","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1335":"1335","ABT    1330":"umbes 1330","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1287":"1287","1330":"1330","1260":"1260","{Blddn ap Cnfn}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia","of Marchwiail,Maelor Gymraeg,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1260–":"noin 1260–Kuollut","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1287–Male":"1287–Kuollut","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1333–Female":"1333–Kuollut","1335–Female":"1335–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","about 1260":"noin 1260","1335":"1335","ABT    1330":"noin 1330","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1287":"1287","1330":"1330","1260":"1260","{Blddn ap Cnfn}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italia","of Marchwiail,Maelor Gymraeg,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 12